Jackson. ''The Bronx: Lost, Found, and Remembered, 1935\u20131975'' (1999) [http://www.h-net.org/reviews/showrev.php?id=2982 online review], nostalgia\n* [[Lloyd Ultan (historian)|Ultan, Lloyd]]. ''The Northern Borough: A History Of The Bronx'' (2009), popular general history\n* Ultan, Lloyd. ''The Bronx in the frontier era: from the beginning to 1696'' (1994)\n* Ultan, Lloyd. ''The Beautiful Bronx (1920\u20131950)'' (1979), heavily illustrated\n* Ultan, Lloyd. ''The Birth of the Bronx, 1609\u20131900'' (2000), popular\n* Ultan, Lloyd. ''The Bronx in the innocent years, 1890\u20131925'' (1985), popular\n* Ultan, Lloyd. ''The Bronx: It Was Only Yesterday, \"The Bronx: It Was Only Yesterday 1935\u20131965'' (1992), heavily illustrated popular history\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|commons=Category:The Bronx, New York City|voy=Bronx|s=1911 Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica/Bronx, The}}\n* [http://bronxboropres.nyc.gov/ Bronx Borough President's Office]\n* {{curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/New_York/Localities/N/New_York_City/The_Bronx|Bronx County}}\n\n===Newspapers===\n* [http://www.bxtimes.com/ The Bronx Times Reporter]\n* [http://www.bronx.com/ The Bronx Times]\n* [http://www.innercitypress.org/bxreport.html Weekly Bronx Report from Inner City Press]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151025032510/http://brie.hunter.cuny.edu/hpe/ The Hunts Point Express]\n* [http://www.motthavenherald.com/ The Mott Haven Herald]\n* [http://www.norwoodnews.org/The Norwood News]\n* [http://www.riverdalepress.com/ The Riverdale Press]\n\n===Associations===\n* [http://bronxriver.org/ The Bronx River Alliance]\n* [http://www.bceq.org/ Bronx Council for Environmental Quality]\n* [http://www.throggsneckmerchants.com/ Throggs Neck Merchant Association]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120708113524/http://www.thebronxmarket.com/ The Bronx Market]\n* [http://www.sobro.org/ The South Bronx Overall Economic Development Corporation]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111105050545/http://nybronx.org/ Bronx County, NY Website ]\n\n===History===\n* [http://www.cityislandmuseum.org/ City Island Nautical Museum]\n* [http://www.bronxnyc.com/ East Bronx History Forum]\n* [http://www.kingsbridgehistoricalsociety.org/KHS/Home.html Kingsbridge Historical Society]\n* [http://www.bronxhistoricalsociety.org/ Museum of Bronx History]\n* [http://www.bronxhistoricalsociety.org/ The Bronx County Historical Society]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040825075222/http://www.ancestry.com/library/view/ancmag/762.asp The Bronx: A Swedish Connection]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=ruhKAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA700 Report of the Bronx Parkway Commission, December 31, 1918], retrieved on July 24, 2008\n* [http://www.bronxsynagogues.org/ Remembrance of Synagogues Past: The Lost Civilization of the Jewish South Bronx] by Seymour Perlin, retrieved on August 10, 2008\n* [http://www.forgotten-ny.com/ Forgotten New York: Relics of a Rich History in the Everyday Life of New York City]\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre = Bronx County, New York\n|North = [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]]\n|Northeast =\n|East = [[Eastchester Bay]]\n|Southeast =\n|South = [[Queens|Queens County<br />(Queens)]]\n|Southwest = [[Manhattan|New York County<br />(Manhattan)]]\n|West = [[Bergen County, New Jersey]]\n|Northwest =\n}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Bronx}}\n{{New York City}}\n{{New York metropolitan area}}\n{{New York}}\n{{Northeastern U.S. majority-minority counties}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bronx, The}}\n[[Category:The Bronx| ]]\n[[Category:Boroughs of New York City]]\n[[Category:County seats in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1898]]\n[[Category:1898 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Alter: title. | You canuse this toolyourself.Report bugs here. | via #UCB_Gadget", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Bronx"}
{"title_page": "Prague Castle", "text_new": "{{Infobox Historic building\n|name=Prague Castle\n|native_name = Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad\n|image=Czech-2013-Prague-View from Charles Bridge of Prague Castle.jpg\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption = Prague Castle\n|location = [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]]\n|current_tenants=[[Milo\u0161 Zeman]]<br>{{small|(2013\u2013present)}}\n|architect=[[Matthias of Arras]], [[Peter Parler]]\n|floor_area=<!-- {{convert|55000|sqft|abbr=on}} -->\n|start_date= 870\n|completion_date = 1929\n|style=[[Baroque]], [[Mannerism]]\n|website= [http://www.hrad.cz/en www.hrad.cz]\n}}\n\n'''Prague Castle''' ({{lang-cs|Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad}}; {{IPA-cs|\u02c8pra\u0283ski\u02d0 \u02c8\u0266rat|}}) is a [[castle]] complex in [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]], built in the 9th century. It is the official office of the [[President of the Czech Republic]]. The castle was a seat of power for [[List of rulers of Bohemia|kings of Bohemia]], [[Holy Roman Empire|Holy Roman emperors]], and [[List of Presidents of Czechoslovakia|presidents]] of [[Czechoslovakia]]. The [[Bohemian Crown Jewels]] are kept within a hidden room inside it.\n\nAccording to the [[Guinness Book of Records]], Prague Castle is the largest ancient castle in the world,<ref>{{cite book|title=Guinness World Records 2015|year=2014|publisher=Guinness World Records|isbn=9781908843708|page=[https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldrec0000unse_f8z3/page/199 199]|url=https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldrec0000unse_f8z3|url-access=registration|quote=Guinness World Records 2015.|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Guinness Book of Records entry on Prague Castle|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/content_pages/record.asp?recordid=50103|publisher=Guinness World Records|date=21 July 2006|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060721043205/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/content_pages/record.asp?recordid=50103|archivedate=21 July 2006}}</ref> occupying an area of almost {{convert|70000|m2|ft2|abbr=off}}, at about {{convert|570|m|ft|abbr=off}} in length and an average of about {{convert|130|m|ft|abbr=off}} wide. The castle is among the most visited [[tourist attraction]]s in Prague attracting over 1.8  million visitors annually.<ref>[http://www.nipos-mk.cz/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/Statistika_2015_I.KULTURNI_DEDICTVI_web.pdf NIPOS: Z\u00e1kladn\u00ed statistick\u00e9 \u00fadaje o kultu\u0159e v \u010cesk\u00e9 republice - I. d\u00edl - kulturn\u00ed d\u011bdictv\u00ed (muzea, galerie a pam\u00e1tkov\u00e9 objekty)]</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Praha Hrad 1607.jpg|thumb|Prague Castle in 1607]] yo g dawg\n[[Image:FFridrich, Praha, Karluv most a Prazsky hrad.jpg|thumb|Prague Castle in 1870]]\n[[Image:Prag Vladislav-Saal.jpg|thumb|upright|Vladislav Hall]]\n[[File:Praha, Hradn\u00ed str\u00e1\u017e 05.jpg|thumb|Changing of the [[Prague Castle Guard|Guards]]]]\n[[File:Prag Burgwache Wachabl\u00f6sung st\u00fcndlich.webm|thumb|Changing of the Guards (2016)]]\n\n===P\u0159emyslid fort===\nThe history of the castle began in 870 when its first walled building, the [[Church of the Virgin Mary (Prague Castle)|Church of the Virgin Mary]], was built.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theculturetrip.com/europe/czech-republic/articles/a-brief-history-of-the-prague-castle/|title=A Brief History of the Prague Castle|last=Bocco|first=Diana|website=Culture Trip|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref> The [[St. George's Basilica, Prague|Basilica of Saint George]] and the [[St. Vitus Cathedral|Basilica of St. Vitus]] were founded under the reign of [[Vratislaus I, Duke of Bohemia]] and his son [[Wenceslaus I, Duke of Bohemia|St. Wenceslas]] in the first half of the 10th century.\n\nThe first convent in [[Bohemia]] was founded in the castle, next to the church of St. George. A Romanesque palace was erected here during the 12th century.\n\n===Medieval castle===\nKing [[Ottokar II of Bohemia]] improved fortifications and rebuilt the royal palace for the purposes of representation and housing. In the 14th century, under the reign of [[Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles IV]] the royal palace was rebuilt in [[Gothic architecture|Gothic style]] and the castle fortifications were strengthened. In place of rotunda and basilica of St. Vitus began building of a vast Gothic church, that were completed almost six centuries later.\n\nDuring the [[Hussite Wars]] and the following decades, the castle was not inhabited. In 1485, King [[Vladislaus II of Hungary]] began to rebuild the castle. The massive Vladislav Hall (built by [[Benedikt Rejt]]) was added to the Royal Palace. New defence towers were also built on the north side of the castle.\n\nA large fire in 1541 destroyed large parts of the castle. Under the [[Habsburgs]], some new buildings in [[renaissance architecture|Renaissance]] style were added. [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]] built the Belvedere as a summer palace for his wife [[Anna of Bohemia and Hungary|Anne]]. [[Rudolph II]] used Prague Castle as his main residence. He founded the northern wing of the palace, with the [[Spanish Hall (Prague Castle)|Spanish Hall]], where his precious art collections were exhibited.\n\nThe Third [[Defenestrations of Prague|Defenestration of Prague]] in 1618 took place at the castle and began the Bohemian Revolt. During the subsequent wars, the Castle was damaged and dilapidated. Many works from  the collection of [[Rudolph II]] were looted by Swedes in 1648, in the [[Battle of Prague (1648)]] which was the final act of the [[Thirty Years' War]].\n\nThe last major rebuilding of the castle was carried out by [[Empress Maria Theresa]] in the second half of the 18th century. Following his abdication in 1848, and the succession of his nephew, [[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Franz Joseph]], to the throne, the former emperor, [[Ferdinand I of Austria|Ferdinand I]], made Prague Castle his home.\n\n===Presidential residence===\n[[File:Charles Bridge (Karl\u016fv most), Vltava River, Prague, 2015.jpg|thumb|Charles Bridge (Karl\u016fv most), Vltava River, Castle on the hilltop]]\nIn 1918, the castle became the seat of the president of the new [[First Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovak Republic]], [[T.G. Masaryk]]. The New Royal Palace and the gardens were renovated by Slovenian architect [[Jo\u017ee Ple\u010dnik]]. In this period the [[St Vitus Cathedral]] was finished (on September 28, 1929).  Renovations continued in 1936 under Ple\u010dnik's successor [[Pavel Jan\u00e1k]].\n\nOn March 15, 1939, shortly after the [[Nazi Germany]] forced Czech President [[Emil Hacha]] (who suffered a heart attack during the negotiations) to hand his nation over to the Germans, [[Adolf Hitler]] spent a night in the Prague Castle, \"proudly surveying his new possession.\"<ref>Klaus Fischer, ''Nazi Germany: A New History'' (New York: Continuum, 1995), p. 433.</ref> During the Nazi occupation of Czechoslovakia in World War II, Prague Castle became the headquarters of [[Reinhard Heydrich]], the Reich Protector of Bohemia and Moravia. According to a popular rumor, he is said to have placed the Bohemian crown on his head; old legends say a [[usurper]] who places the crown on his head is doomed to die within a year.<ref>Mirna Solic, ''The gate open to the Bohemian crown jewels'' at [http://www.radio.cz/en/article/42583 Radio Prague].</ref> Less than a year after assuming power, on May 27, 1942, Heydrich was ambushed during [[Operation Anthropoid]], by British-trained Slovak and Czech resistance soldiers while on his way to the Castle, and died of his wounds - which became infected - a week later.<ref>Gerald Reitlinger, ''The SS: Alibi of a Nation, 1922-1945'' (New York: Da Capo Press, 1989), p. 215.</ref> Klaus, his [[firstborn son]], died the next year in a traffic accident, also in line with the legend.<ref>http://spartacus-educational.com/Lina_Heydrich.htm</ref>\n\nAfter the liberation of Czechoslovakia and the [[1948 Czechoslovak coup d'\u00e9tat|coup in 1948]], the Castle housed the offices of the communist Czechoslovak government. After [[Dissolution of Czechoslovakia|Czechoslovakia split]] in 1993 into the Czech Republic and Slovakia, the castle became the seat of the [[List of presidents of the Czech Republic|Head of State]] of the new Czech Republic.  Similar to what Masaryk did with Ple\u010dnik, president [[V\u00e1clav Havel]] commissioned [[Bo\u0159ek \u0160\u00edpek]] to be the architect of post-communism Prague Castle's necessary improvements, in particular of the facelift of the castle's gallery of paintings.\n\n==Architectural styles of Prague Castle==\n[[Image:St Vitus Prague September 2016-21.jpg|thumb|right|[[St. Vitus Cathedral|Saint Vitus Cathedral]]]]\n[[Image:St Vitus Prague September 2016-2.jpg|thumb|right|Main nave of the cathedral]]\nThe castle buildings represent virtually every architectural style of the last millennium. Prague Castle includes [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] [[St Vitus Cathedral]], [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] [[St. George's Basilica, Prague|Basilica of St. George]], a monastery and several palaces, gardens and defense towers. Most of the castle areas are open to tourists. The castle houses several museums, including the [[National Gallery in Prague|National Gallery]] collection of Bohemian [[baroque]] and [[mannerism]] art, exhibition  dedicated to Czech history, Toy Museum and the picture gallery of Prague Castle, based on the collection of Rudolph II. The [[Summer Shakespeare Festival]] regularly takes place in the courtyard of Burgrave Palace.\n\nThe neighborhood around Prague Castle is called [[Hrad\u010dany]].\n\n===Churches===\n[[Image:Prague Castle St George.JPG|thumb|right|[[St. George's Basilica, Prague|Basilica of St George]]]]\n[[File:Czech crown jewels.jpg|thumb|The [[Bohemian Crown Jewels|Czech Crown Jewels]] are the fourth oldest in Europe]]\n[[File:2014 Praga, Hradczany.JPG|thumb|New Provost Residence]]\n* Katedr\u00e1la svat\u00e9ho V\u00edta, V\u00e1clava a Vojt\u011bcha ([[St. Vitus Cathedral]])\n* Bazilika svat\u00e9ho Ji\u0159\u00ed ([[St. George's Basilica, Prague]]) and Kl\u00e1\u0161ter svat\u00e9ho Ji\u0159\u00ed ([[St. George's Convent, Prague]]), it is the oldest surviving church building within Prague Castle.\n* Chr\u00e1m V\u0161ech svat\u00fdch ([[All Saints Church (Prague Castle)|All Saints Church]])\n* Kaple svat\u00e9ho K\u0159\u00ed\u017ee ({{ill|Holy Cross Chapel|cs|Kaple svat\u00e9ho K\u0159\u00ed\u017ee (Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad)}})\n\n===Palaces===\n* Star\u00fd kr\u00e1lovsk\u00fd pal\u00e1c ([[Old Royal Palace (Prague)|Old Royal Palace]])\n* Letohr\u00e1dek kr\u00e1lovny Anny ({{ill|Belvedere (Prague)|cs|Letohr\u00e1dek kr\u00e1lovny Anny}})\n* Lobkovick\u00fd pal\u00e1c ([[Lobkowicz Palace]], not to be confused with the [[Embassy of Germany in Prague|German embassy]] in [[Mal\u00e1 Strana]])\n* Nov\u00fd kr\u00e1lovsk\u00fd pal\u00e1c ({{ill|New Royal Palace (Prague)|cs|Nov\u00fd kr\u00e1lovsk\u00fd pal\u00e1c}})\n\n=== Halls ===\n* Sloupov\u00e1 s\u00ed\u0148 ({{ill|Column Hall|cs|Sloupov\u00e1 s\u00ed\u0148 Pra\u017esk\u00e9ho hradu}})\n* \u0160pan\u011blsk\u00fd s\u00e1l ([[Spanish Hall (Prague Castle)|Spanish Hall]])\n* Rudolfova galerie ({{ill|Rudolph's Gallery|cs|Rudolfova galerie}}) \n* Rothmayer\u016fv s\u00e1l ({{ill|Rothmayer's Hall|cs|Rothmayer\u016fv s\u00e1l}})\n* Vladislavsk\u00fd s\u00e1l ([[Vladislav Hall]])\n\n===Towers===\n* B\u00edl\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e ({{ill|White Tower (Prague Castle)|cs|B\u00edl\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e (Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad)}})\n* \u010cern\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e ({{ill|Black Tower (Prague Castle)|cs|\u010cern\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e (Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad)}})\n* Daliborka ({{ill|Dalibor Tower|cs|Daliborka}})\n* Pra\u0161n\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e or Mihulka ({{ill|Mihulka|cs|Mihulka}})\n\n===Other buildings===\n* Zlat\u00e1 uli\u010dka ([[Golden Lane]])\n* Star\u00e9 purkrabstv\u00ed ({{ill|Old Supreme Burgrave's House|cs|Star\u00e9 purkrabstv\u00ed}} )\n* M\u00ed\u010dovna ({{ill|Ball Game Hall|cs|M\u00ed\u010dovna (Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad)}}) \n* J\u00edzd\u00e1rna Pra\u017esk\u00e9ho hradu ({{ill|Riding School|cs|J\u00edzd\u00e1rna Pra\u017esk\u00e9ho hradu}})\n* Star\u00e9 probo\u0161tstv\u00ed ({{ill|Old Provost Residence|cs|Star\u00e9 probo\u0161tstv\u00ed}} )\n* Nov\u00e9 probo\u0161tstv\u00ed ({{ill|New Provost Residence|cs|Nov\u00e9 probo\u0161tstv\u00ed}})\n*Pra\u0161n\u00fd most ({{ill|Pra\u0161n\u00fd Bridge|cs|Pra\u0161n\u00fd most|lt=|WD=}})\n\n===Gardens===\n[[Image:Svatovaclavska vinice.jpg|thumb|right|Svatov\u00e1clavsk\u00e1 vinice (St. Wenceslas' Vineyard) on east]]\n* Kr\u00e1lovsk\u00e1 zahrada ([[Royal Garden of Prague Castle]])\n** Oran\u017e\u00e9rie ([[Orangery (Royal Garden of Prague Castle)|Orangery]])  \n* Zahrada na terase J\u00edzd\u00e1rny ({{ill|Riding School Terrace Garden|cs|Zahrada na terase J\u00edzd\u00e1rny}}) \n* Zahrada Na Ba\u0161t\u011b (The Garden on the Bastion) \n* Ji\u017en\u00ed zahrady (South Gardens)\n** Rajsk\u00e1 zahrada ({{ill|Paradise Garden (Prague Castle)|cs|Rajsk\u00e1 zahrada (Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad)|lt=Paradise Garden}})\n** Zahrada Na Valech ({{ill|Garden on the Ramparts|cs|Zahrada Na Valech}}) \n** Hartigovsk\u00e1 zahrada ({{ill|The Hartig Garden|cs|Hartigovsk\u00e1 zahrada}})\n* Jelen\u00ed p\u0159\u00edkop ([[Deer Moat]])\n* Svatov\u00e1clavsk\u00e1 vinice ({{ill|St. Wenceslas vineyard|cs|Svatov\u00e1clavsk\u00e1 vinice}})\n* Produk\u010dn\u00ed zahrady Pra\u017esk\u00e9ho hradu ({{ill|Horticultural Gardens|cs|Produk\u010dn\u00ed zahrady Pra\u017esk\u00e9ho hradu}})\n\n==Structures==\n* Kohlova ka\u0161na ([[Kohl's Fountain]])\n* Maty\u00e1\u0161ova br\u00e1na ([[Matthias Gate]])\n* Obelisk  ([[Obelisk (Prague Castle)|Obelisk]])\n* Socha svat\u00e9ho Ji\u0159\u00ed ([[Statue of Saint George, Prague Castle|Statue of Saint George]])\n\n==In popular culture==\nPrague Castle is the location in the second level of ''[[Indiana Jones and the Emperor's Tomb]]'' video game.\n\nIt is also mentioned in the video game ''[[Assassin's Creed IV Black Flag]]'' as a hidden file found in a hacked computer at Abstergo Entertainment.\n\nIt is briefly shown in the Japanese manga and its anime adaptation ''[[Monster (manga)|Monster]]'' when some of the main characters visit Prague.\n\nPrague Castle served as a Pit Stop for both the [[The Amazing Race 15|fifteenth season]] of the [[The Amazing Race (American TV series)|American ''Amazing Race'']]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/the-amazing-race-pointers-from-prague/|title=The Amazing Race: Pointers from Prague|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=23 November 2009|accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref> and the [[The Amazing Race Australia 1|first season]] of the [[The Amazing Race Australia|Australian ''Amazing Race'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesupacoowackiestblogintheuniverse.wordpress.com/2017/05/20/the-amazing-race-australia-1-episode-six-rankings/|title=The Amazing Race Australia 1 Episode Six Rankings|work=Thesupacoowackiestblogintheuniverse's Blog|last=Saunders|first=Logan|date=20 May 2017|accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of early modern period domes]]\n* [[Prague Castle skeleton]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last1=Di Duca|first1=Marc|title=Rough Guide to Prague|date=2015|publisher=Rough Guides Ltd|isbn=9780241196311|ref=harv}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n* Fischer, Klaus. ''Nazi Germany: A New History''. New York: Continuum, 1995.\n* Reitlinger, Gerald. ''The SS: Alibi of a Nation, 1922-1945''. New York: Da Capo Press, 1989.\n* [http://www.hrad.cz/cs/prazsky-hrad/virtualni-prohlidka/index.shtml Virtual visit with map and written commentary (in czech)]\n* [https://www.hrad.cz/en/prague-castle-for-visitors/photogallery Virtual visit with map and written commentary (in English)]\n* [http://www.czechtourism.com/c/prague-castle Tourist information] - Official tourist website\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150210105516/http://www.hrad.cz/en/prazsky_hrad/navsteva_hradu.shtml Prague Castle] - Official website \n* [http://old.hrad.cz/index_uk.html History of Prague Castle] \n\n{{Prague Castle}}\n{{Imperial and Royal residences}}\n{{Coord|50|05.385|N|14|23.904|E|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Attached KML}}\n\n[[Category:Prague Castle| ]]\n[[Category:Presidential residences]]\n[[Category:Jo\u017ee Ple\u010dnik buildings]]\n[[Category:National Cultural Monuments of the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Castles in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Prague]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Historic building\n|name=Prague Castle\n|native_name = Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad\n|image=Czech-2013-Prague-View from Charles Bridge of Prague Castle.jpg\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption = Prague Castle\n|location = [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]]\n|current_tenants=[[Milo\u0161 Zeman]]<br>{{small|(2013\u2013present)}}\n|architect=[[Matthias of Arras]], [[Peter Parler]]\n|floor_area=<!-- {{convert|55000|sqft|abbr=on}} -->\n|start_date= 870\n|completion_date = 1929\n|style=[[Baroque]], [[Mannerism]]\n|website= [http://www.hrad.cz/en www.hrad.cz]\n}}\n\n'''Prague Castle''' ({{lang-cs|Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad}}; {{IPA-cs|\u02c8pra\u0283ski\u02d0 \u02c8\u0266rat|}}) is a [[castle]] complex in [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]], built in the 9th century. It is the official office of the [[President of the Czech Republic]]. The castle was a seat of power for [[List of rulers of Bohemia|kings of Bohemia]], [[Holy Roman Empire|Holy Roman emperors]], and [[List of Presidents of Czechoslovakia|presidents]] of [[Czechoslovakia]]. The [[Bohemian Crown Jewels]] are kept within a hidden room inside it.\n\nAccording to the [[Guinness Book of Records]], Prague Castle is the largest ancient castle in the world,<ref>{{cite book|title=Guinness World Records 2015|year=2014|publisher=Guinness World Records|isbn=9781908843708|page=[https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldrec0000unse_f8z3/page/199 199]|url=https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldrec0000unse_f8z3|url-access=registration|quote=Guinness World Records 2015.|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Guinness Book of Records entry on Prague Castle|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/content_pages/record.asp?recordid=50103|publisher=Guinness World Records|date=21 July 2006|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060721043205/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/content_pages/record.asp?recordid=50103|archivedate=21 July 2006}}</ref> occupying an area of almost {{convert|70000|m2|ft2|abbr=off}}, at about {{convert|570|m|ft|abbr=off}} in length and an average of about {{convert|130|m|ft|abbr=off}} wide. The castle is among the most visited [[tourist attraction]]s in Prague attracting over 1.8  million visitors annually.<ref>[http://www.nipos-mk.cz/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/Statistika_2015_I.KULTURNI_DEDICTVI_web.pdf NIPOS: Z\u00e1kladn\u00ed statistick\u00e9 \u00fadaje o kultu\u0159e v \u010cesk\u00e9 republice - I. d\u00edl - kulturn\u00ed d\u011bdictv\u00ed (muzea, galerie a pam\u00e1tkov\u00e9 objekty)]</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Praha Hrad 1607.jpg|thumb|Prague Castle in 1607]]\n[[Image:FFridrich, Praha, Karluv most a Prazsky hrad.jpg|thumb|Prague Castle in 1870]]\n[[Image:Prag Vladislav-Saal.jpg|thumb|upright|Vladislav Hall]]\n[[File:Praha, Hradn\u00ed str\u00e1\u017e 05.jpg|thumb|Changing of the [[Prague Castle Guard|Guards]]]]\n[[File:Prag Burgwache Wachabl\u00f6sung st\u00fcndlich.webm|thumb|Changing of the Guards (2016)]]\n\n===P\u0159emyslid fort===\nThe history of the castle began in 870 when its first walled building, the [[Church of the Virgin Mary (Prague Castle)|Church of the Virgin Mary]], was built.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theculturetrip.com/europe/czech-republic/articles/a-brief-history-of-the-prague-castle/|title=A Brief History of the Prague Castle|last=Bocco|first=Diana|website=Culture Trip|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref> The [[St. George's Basilica, Prague|Basilica of Saint George]] and the [[St. Vitus Cathedral|Basilica of St. Vitus]] were founded under the reign of [[Vratislaus I, Duke of Bohemia]] and his son [[Wenceslaus I, Duke of Bohemia|St. Wenceslas]] in the first half of the 10th century.\n\nThe first convent in [[Bohemia]] was founded in the castle, next to the church of St. George. A Romanesque palace was erected here during the 12th century.\n\n===Medieval castle===\nKing [[Ottokar II of Bohemia]] improved fortifications and rebuilt the royal palace for the purposes of representation and housing. In the 14th century, under the reign of [[Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles IV]] the royal palace was rebuilt in [[Gothic architecture|Gothic style]] and the castle fortifications were strengthened. In place of rotunda and basilica of St. Vitus began building of a vast Gothic church, that were completed almost six centuries later.\n\nDuring the [[Hussite Wars]] and the following decades, the castle was not inhabited. In 1485, King [[Vladislaus II of Hungary]] began to rebuild the castle. The massive Vladislav Hall (built by [[Benedikt Rejt]]) was added to the Royal Palace. New defence towers were also built on the north side of the castle.\n\nA large fire in 1541 destroyed large parts of the castle. Under the [[Habsburgs]], some new buildings in [[renaissance architecture|Renaissance]] style were added. [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]] built the Belvedere as a summer palace for his wife [[Anna of Bohemia and Hungary|Anne]]. [[Rudolph II]] used Prague Castle as his main residence. He founded the northern wing of the palace, with the [[Spanish Hall (Prague Castle)|Spanish Hall]], where his precious art collections were exhibited.\n\nThe Third [[Defenestrations of Prague|Defenestration of Prague]] in 1618 took place at the castle and began the Bohemian Revolt. During the subsequent wars, the Castle was damaged and dilapidated. Many works from  the collection of [[Rudolph II]] were looted by Swedes in 1648, in the [[Battle of Prague (1648)]] which was the final act of the [[Thirty Years' War]].\n\nThe last major rebuilding of the castle was carried out by [[Empress Maria Theresa]] in the second half of the 18th century. Following his abdication in 1848, and the succession of his nephew, [[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Franz Joseph]], to the throne, the former emperor, [[Ferdinand I of Austria|Ferdinand I]], made Prague Castle his home.\n\n===Presidential residence===\n[[File:Charles Bridge (Karl\u016fv most), Vltava River, Prague, 2015.jpg|thumb|Charles Bridge (Karl\u016fv most), Vltava River, Castle on the hilltop]]\nIn 1918, the castle became the seat of the president of the new [[First Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovak Republic]], [[T.G. Masaryk]]. The New Royal Palace and the gardens were renovated by Slovenian architect [[Jo\u017ee Ple\u010dnik]]. In this period the [[St Vitus Cathedral]] was finished (on September 28, 1929).  Renovations continued in 1936 under Ple\u010dnik's successor [[Pavel Jan\u00e1k]].\n\nOn March 15, 1939, shortly after the [[Nazi Germany]] forced Czech President [[Emil Hacha]] (who suffered a heart attack during the negotiations) to hand his nation over to the Germans, [[Adolf Hitler]] spent a night in the Prague Castle, \"proudly surveying his new possession.\"<ref>Klaus Fischer, ''Nazi Germany: A New History'' (New York: Continuum, 1995), p. 433.</ref> During the Nazi occupation of Czechoslovakia in World War II, Prague Castle became the headquarters of [[Reinhard Heydrich]], the Reich Protector of Bohemia and Moravia. According to a popular rumor, he is said to have placed the Bohemian crown on his head; old legends say a [[usurper]] who places the crown on his head is doomed to die within a year.<ref>Mirna Solic, ''The gate open to the Bohemian crown jewels'' at [http://www.radio.cz/en/article/42583 Radio Prague].</ref> Less than a year after assuming power, on May 27, 1942, Heydrich was ambushed during [[Operation Anthropoid]], by British-trained Slovak and Czech resistance soldiers while on his way to the Castle, and died of his wounds - which became infected - a week later.<ref>Gerald Reitlinger, ''The SS: Alibi of a Nation, 1922-1945'' (New York: Da Capo Press, 1989), p. 215.</ref> Klaus, his [[firstborn son]], died the next year in a traffic accident, also in line with the legend.<ref>http://spartacus-educational.com/Lina_Heydrich.htm</ref>\n\nAfter the liberation of Czechoslovakia and the [[1948 Czechoslovak coup d'\u00e9tat|coup in 1948]], the Castle housed the offices of the communist Czechoslovak government. After [[Dissolution of Czechoslovakia|Czechoslovakia split]] in 1993 into the Czech Republic and Slovakia, the castle became the seat of the [[List of presidents of the Czech Republic|Head of State]] of the new Czech Republic.  Similar to what Masaryk did with Ple\u010dnik, president [[V\u00e1clav Havel]] commissioned [[Bo\u0159ek \u0160\u00edpek]] to be the architect of post-communism Prague Castle's necessary improvements, in particular of the facelift of the castle's gallery of paintings.\n\n==Architectural styles of Prague Castle==\n[[Image:St Vitus Prague September 2016-21.jpg|thumb|right|[[St. Vitus Cathedral|Saint Vitus Cathedral]]]]\n[[Image:St Vitus Prague September 2016-2.jpg|thumb|right|Main nave of the cathedral]]\nThe castle buildings represent virtually every architectural style of the last millennium. Prague Castle includes [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] [[St Vitus Cathedral]], [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] [[St. George's Basilica, Prague|Basilica of St. George]], a monastery and several palaces, gardens and defense towers. Most of the castle areas are open to tourists. The castle houses several museums, including the [[National Gallery in Prague|National Gallery]] collection of Bohemian [[baroque]] and [[mannerism]] art, exhibition  dedicated to Czech history, Toy Museum and the picture gallery of Prague Castle, based on the collection of Rudolph II. The [[Summer Shakespeare Festival]] regularly takes place in the courtyard of Burgrave Palace.\n\nThe neighborhood around Prague Castle is called [[Hrad\u010dany]].\n\n===Churches===\n[[Image:Prague Castle St George.JPG|thumb|right|[[St. George's Basilica, Prague|Basilica of St George]]]]\n[[File:Czech crown jewels.jpg|thumb|The [[Bohemian Crown Jewels|Czech Crown Jewels]] are the fourth oldest in Europe]]\n[[File:2014 Praga, Hradczany.JPG|thumb|New Provost Residence]]\n* Katedr\u00e1la svat\u00e9ho V\u00edta, V\u00e1clava a Vojt\u011bcha ([[St. Vitus Cathedral]])\n* Bazilika svat\u00e9ho Ji\u0159\u00ed ([[St. George's Basilica, Prague]]) and Kl\u00e1\u0161ter svat\u00e9ho Ji\u0159\u00ed ([[St. George's Convent, Prague]]), it is the oldest surviving church building within Prague Castle.\n* Chr\u00e1m V\u0161ech svat\u00fdch ([[All Saints Church (Prague Castle)|All Saints Church]])\n* Kaple svat\u00e9ho K\u0159\u00ed\u017ee ({{ill|Holy Cross Chapel|cs|Kaple svat\u00e9ho K\u0159\u00ed\u017ee (Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad)}})\n\n===Palaces===\n* Star\u00fd kr\u00e1lovsk\u00fd pal\u00e1c ([[Old Royal Palace (Prague)|Old Royal Palace]])\n* Letohr\u00e1dek kr\u00e1lovny Anny ({{ill|Belvedere (Prague)|cs|Letohr\u00e1dek kr\u00e1lovny Anny}})\n* Lobkovick\u00fd pal\u00e1c ([[Lobkowicz Palace]], not to be confused with the [[Embassy of Germany in Prague|German embassy]] in [[Mal\u00e1 Strana]])\n* Nov\u00fd kr\u00e1lovsk\u00fd pal\u00e1c ({{ill|New Royal Palace (Prague)|cs|Nov\u00fd kr\u00e1lovsk\u00fd pal\u00e1c}})\n\n=== Halls ===\n* Sloupov\u00e1 s\u00ed\u0148 ({{ill|Column Hall|cs|Sloupov\u00e1 s\u00ed\u0148 Pra\u017esk\u00e9ho hradu}})\n* \u0160pan\u011blsk\u00fd s\u00e1l ([[Spanish Hall (Prague Castle)|Spanish Hall]])\n* Rudolfova galerie ({{ill|Rudolph's Gallery|cs|Rudolfova galerie}}) \n* Rothmayer\u016fv s\u00e1l ({{ill|Rothmayer's Hall|cs|Rothmayer\u016fv s\u00e1l}})\n* Vladislavsk\u00fd s\u00e1l ([[Vladislav Hall]])\n\n===Towers===\n* B\u00edl\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e ({{ill|White Tower (Prague Castle)|cs|B\u00edl\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e (Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad)}})\n* \u010cern\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e ({{ill|Black Tower (Prague Castle)|cs|\u010cern\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e (Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad)}})\n* Daliborka ({{ill|Dalibor Tower|cs|Daliborka}})\n* Pra\u0161n\u00e1 v\u011b\u017e or Mihulka ({{ill|Mihulka|cs|Mihulka}})\n\n===Other buildings===\n* Zlat\u00e1 uli\u010dka ([[Golden Lane]])\n* Star\u00e9 purkrabstv\u00ed ({{ill|Old Supreme Burgrave's House|cs|Star\u00e9 purkrabstv\u00ed}} )\n* M\u00ed\u010dovna ({{ill|Ball Game Hall|cs|M\u00ed\u010dovna (Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad)}}) \n* J\u00edzd\u00e1rna Pra\u017esk\u00e9ho hradu ({{ill|Riding School|cs|J\u00edzd\u00e1rna Pra\u017esk\u00e9ho hradu}})\n* Star\u00e9 probo\u0161tstv\u00ed ({{ill|Old Provost Residence|cs|Star\u00e9 probo\u0161tstv\u00ed}} )\n* Nov\u00e9 probo\u0161tstv\u00ed ({{ill|New Provost Residence|cs|Nov\u00e9 probo\u0161tstv\u00ed}})\n*Pra\u0161n\u00fd most ({{ill|Pra\u0161n\u00fd Bridge|cs|Pra\u0161n\u00fd most|lt=|WD=}})\n\n===Gardens===\n[[Image:Svatovaclavska vinice.jpg|thumb|right|Svatov\u00e1clavsk\u00e1 vinice (St. Wenceslas' Vineyard) on east]]\n* Kr\u00e1lovsk\u00e1 zahrada ([[Royal Garden of Prague Castle]])\n** Oran\u017e\u00e9rie ([[Orangery (Royal Garden of Prague Castle)|Orangery]])  \n* Zahrada na terase J\u00edzd\u00e1rny ({{ill|Riding School Terrace Garden|cs|Zahrada na terase J\u00edzd\u00e1rny}}) \n* Zahrada Na Ba\u0161t\u011b (The Garden on the Bastion) \n* Ji\u017en\u00ed zahrady (South Gardens)\n** Rajsk\u00e1 zahrada ({{ill|Paradise Garden (Prague Castle)|cs|Rajsk\u00e1 zahrada (Pra\u017esk\u00fd hrad)|lt=Paradise Garden}})\n** Zahrada Na Valech ({{ill|Garden on the Ramparts|cs|Zahrada Na Valech}}) \n** Hartigovsk\u00e1 zahrada ({{ill|The Hartig Garden|cs|Hartigovsk\u00e1 zahrada}})\n* Jelen\u00ed p\u0159\u00edkop ([[Deer Moat]])\n* Svatov\u00e1clavsk\u00e1 vinice ({{ill|St. Wenceslas vineyard|cs|Svatov\u00e1clavsk\u00e1 vinice}})\n* Produk\u010dn\u00ed zahrady Pra\u017esk\u00e9ho hradu ({{ill|Horticultural Gardens|cs|Produk\u010dn\u00ed zahrady Pra\u017esk\u00e9ho hradu}})\n\n==Structures==\n* Kohlova ka\u0161na ([[Kohl's Fountain]])\n* Maty\u00e1\u0161ova br\u00e1na ([[Matthias Gate]])\n* Obelisk  ([[Obelisk (Prague Castle)|Obelisk]])\n* Socha svat\u00e9ho Ji\u0159\u00ed ([[Statue of Saint George, Prague Castle|Statue of Saint George]])\n\n==In popular culture==\nPrague Castle is the location in the second level of ''[[Indiana Jones and the Emperor's Tomb]]'' video game.\n\nIt is also mentioned in the video game ''[[Assassin's Creed IV Black Flag]]'' as a hidden file found in a hacked computer at Abstergo Entertainment.\n\nIt is briefly shown in the Japanese manga and its anime adaptation ''[[Monster (manga)|Monster]]'' when some of the main characters visit Prague.\n\nPrague Castle served as a Pit Stop for both the [[The Amazing Race 15|fifteenth season]] of the [[The Amazing Race (American TV series)|American ''Amazing Race'']]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/the-amazing-race-pointers-from-prague/|title=The Amazing Race: Pointers from Prague|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=23 November 2009|accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref> and the [[The Amazing Race Australia 1|first season]] of the [[The Amazing Race Australia|Australian ''Amazing Race'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesupacoowackiestblogintheuniverse.wordpress.com/2017/05/20/the-amazing-race-australia-1-episode-six-rankings/|title=The Amazing Race Australia 1 Episode Six Rankings|work=Thesupacoowackiestblogintheuniverse's Blog|last=Saunders|first=Logan|date=20 May 2017|accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of early modern period domes]]\n* [[Prague Castle skeleton]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last1=Di Duca|first1=Marc|title=Rough Guide to Prague|date=2015|publisher=Rough Guides Ltd|isbn=9780241196311|ref=harv}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n* Fischer, Klaus. ''Nazi Germany: A New History''. New York: Continuum, 1995.\n* Reitlinger, Gerald. ''The SS: Alibi of a Nation, 1922-1945''. New York: Da Capo Press, 1989.\n* [http://www.hrad.cz/cs/prazsky-hrad/virtualni-prohlidka/index.shtml Virtual visit with map and written commentary (in czech)]\n* [https://www.hrad.cz/en/prague-castle-for-visitors/photogallery Virtual visit with map and written commentary (in English)]\n* [http://www.czechtourism.com/c/prague-castle Tourist information] - Official tourist website\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150210105516/http://www.hrad.cz/en/prazsky_hrad/navsteva_hradu.shtml Prague Castle] - Official website \n* [http://old.hrad.cz/index_uk.html History of Prague Castle] \n\n{{Prague Castle}}\n{{Imperial and Royal residences}}\n{{Coord|50|05.385|N|14|23.904|E|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Attached KML}}\n\n[[Category:Prague Castle| ]]\n[[Category:Presidential residences]]\n[[Category:Jo\u017ee Ple\u010dnik buildings]]\n[[Category:National Cultural Monuments of the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Castles in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Prague]]\n", "name_user": "72.213.178.225", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prague_Castle"}
{"title_page": "Chicken tikka masala", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Chicken tikka}}\n{{redirect|Chicken masala|the Italian dish|Chicken marsala}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Chicken tikka masala\n| image            = Chicken tikka masala.jpg\n| image_size       = 200px\n| caption          = Chicken tikka masala\n| country          = [[Indian subcontinent]]<br>\n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Main course]]\n| served           = Hot\n| main_ingredient  = [[Chicken (food)|Chicken]], [[yogurt]], [[cream]], tomato, onion, garlic, [[ginger]], [[chili pepper]]\n| variations       = Lamb, fish or [[paneer tikka masala]]\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\n[[File:Chicken Tikka Masala KellySue.JPG|thumb|Chicken tikka masala, served atop rice]]\n[[File:Ishwar Chicken Masala.JPG|thumb|Chicken tikka masala in India]]\n'''Chicken tikka masala''' is a dish of chunks of roasted marinated chicken ([[chicken tikka]]) in a spiced [[curry]] sauce. The sauce is usually creamy and orange-coloured. There are multiple claims to its place of origin such as the [[Indian subcontinent]]<ref name=Guardian2001/> and the [[United Kingdom]]. It is among the United Kingdom's most popular dishes.\n\n==Composition==\nChicken tikka masala<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/chicken-tikka-masala|title=Chicken tikka masala {{!}} food|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> is composed of [[chicken tikka]], boneless chunks of chicken marinated in spices and [[yogurt]] that are roasted in an oven, served in a creamy curry sauce.<ref name=\"book\">[[John Lloyd (writer)|Lloyd, J]] and [[John Mitchinson (researcher)|Mitchinson, J]]. ''[[The Book of General Ignorance]]''. Faber & Faber, 2006.</ref> A tomato and [[coriander]] sauce is common, but no recipe for chicken tikka masala is standard; a survey found that of 48 different recipes, the only common ingredient was chicken.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Jackson |first1=Peter |title=A Cultural Politics of Curry in \"Hybrid Cultures, Nervous States: Britain and Germany in a (post)colonial World\"|date=2010|publisher=Rodopi BV|location=Amsterdam|isbn=9789042032286|page=172|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aW4UEN0NUT4C&pg=PA172&lpg=PA172|accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Webb|first1=Andrew|title=Food Britannia|date=2011|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-1847946232|page=177|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FBMLFM305MEC&pg=PA177&lpg=PA177|accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref> The sauce usually includes tomatoes (frequently as [[tomato pur\u00e9e|pur\u00e9e]]), [[cream]], [[coconut cream]] and spices like many versions of its namesake [[masala (spice)|masala]] spice mix. The sauce and chicken pieces may be coloured orange using foodstuffs such as [[turmeric]], [[paprika]], tomato pur\u00e9e or with food dye. The dish shares some similarity with [[butter chicken]], both in the method of creation and appearance.\n\n==Variants==\nVariants of the dish replace chicken with other foodstuffs such as lamb, fish, [[paneer]] or [[Edible mushroom|mushrooms]].\n\n==Origins==\nThe origin of the dish is not certain. Some trace the origins of the dish to the [[British Asian|South Asian community]] in Britain and others claim that the dish was created on the Indian subcontinent. \n\nThe ''Multicultural Handbook of Food, Nutrition and Dietetics'' credits its creation to [[British Bangladeshi|Bangladeshi migrant]] chefs in the 1960s, after migrating from what was then [[East Pakistan]] (now [[Bangladesh]]). At the time, these migrant chefs developed and served a number of new inauthentic \"Indian\" dishes, including chicken tikka masala.<ref name=\"Handbook\">{{cite book |last1=Thaker |first1=Aruna |last2=Barton |first2=Arlene |title=Multicultural Handbook of Food, Nutrition and Dietetics |date=2012 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |isbn=9781405173582 |page=74 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YF1YCg5Ig-EC&pg=PA74}}</ref> Historians of ethnic food Peter and Colleen Grove discuss various origin-claims of chicken tikka masala, concluding that the dish \"was most certainly invented in Britain, probably by a Bangladeshi chef\".<ref name=MenuMag>{{cite web|author1=Grove, Peter |author2=Grove, Colleen|url=http://www.menumagazine.co.uk/book/tikkamasala.html|website=Menu Magazine|publisher=Grove Publications|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127225804/http://www.menumagazine.co.uk/book/tikkamasala.html|archivedate=27 November 2016 |title=Is It or Isn't It? (The Chicken Tikka Masala Story) |date=2008 |accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref> They suggest that \"the shape of things to come may have been a recipe for Shahi Chicken Masala in [[Mrs Balbir Singh]]\u2019s ''Indian Cookery'' published in 1961\".<ref name=MenuMag/>\n\nRahul Verma, a food critic who writes for ''[[The Hindu]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Author profile: Rahul Verma|url=http://www.thehindu.com/profile/author/rahul-verma/|website=The Hindu|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref> said he first tasted the dish in 1971 and that its origins were in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], India. He said \"It's basically a Punjabi dish not more than 40\u201350 years old and must be an accidental discovery which has had periodical improvisations\".<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news |title=Chicken tikka masala debate grows as Indian chefs reprimand Scottish MPs over culinary origins |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/foodanddrink/5972643/Chicken-tikka-masala-row-grows-as-Indian-chefs-reprimand-Scottish-MPs-over-culinary-origins.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | first1=Dean | last1=Nelson | first2=Jalees | last2=Andrabi | date=4 August 2009 | accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Glasgow 2016\"/>\n\nAnother explanation is that it originated in a restaurant in [[Glasgow]], Scotland.<ref name=\"Glasgow 2016\">{{cite news|title=From Charles Mackintosh's waterproof to Dolly the sheep: 43 innovations Scotland has given the world|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/charles-mackintosh-chemist-waterproof-google-doodle-scotland-inventions-innovation-bicycles-a7499911.html|work=The Independent|date=30 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"book\"/> This version recounts how a [[British Pakistani]] chef, Ali Ahmed Aslam, proprietor of the Shish Mahal restaurant in the west end of Glasgow, invented chicken tikka masala by improvising a sauce made from yogurt, cream, and spices.<ref name=\"Glasgow\">{{cite web|title=Glasgow 'invented' Tikka Masala|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/8161812.stm|website=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=21 July 2009|accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Chicken tikka masala claims its origins in Scotland|last1=Godeau| first1=Lucie | agency=Agence France Presse|url=http://www.smh.com.au//breaking-news-world/chicken-tikka-masala-claims-its-origins-in-scotland-20090802-e5mr.html |newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald |date=2 August 2009 |accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref> In 2013, his son Asif Ali told the story of its invention in 1971 to the BBC's ''[[Hairy Bikers]]'' TV cookery programme:<ref name=Bikers/>\n\n{{quote|On a typical dark, wet Glasgow night, a bus driver coming off shift came in and ordered a chicken curry. He sent it back to the waiter saying it's dry. At the time, Dad had an ulcer and was enjoying a plate of tomato soup. So he said why not put some tomato soup into the curry with some spices. They sent it back to the table and the bus driver absolutely loved it. He and his friends came back again and again and we put it on the menu.<ref name=Bikers>BBC Hairy Bikers' Best of British Series 2: 5. Food and the Empire. First shown: 6.30pm 5 April 2013</ref>}}\n\nIn July 2009, then British Member of Parliament [[Mohammad Sarwar (politician)|Mohammad Sarwar]] [[Table (parliamentary procedure)|tabled]] an [[Early Day Motion]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] asking that Parliament support a campaign for Glasgow to be given [[Geographical indications and traditional specialities in the European Union|European Union protected geographical status]] for chicken tikka masala.<ref>{{cite web |title=UK Parliament Early Day Motions 2008-2009 |url=http://edmi.parliament.uk/EDMi/EDMDetails.aspx?EDMID=39136&SESSION=899 |accessdate=11 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222052029/http://edmi.parliament.uk/EDMi/EDMDetails.aspx?EDMID=39136&SESSION=899 |archive-date=22 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Early Day Motion #1911 |url=https://edm.parliament.uk/early-day-motion/39136/glasgow-chicken-tikka-masala |website=House of Commons |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> The motion was not chosen for debate, nor did Sarwar speak on this subject in Parliament.<ref>{{cite web |title=UK Parliament Archives 2008-9 |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200809/cmhansrd/cmallfiles/mps/commons_hansard_564_os.html |accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=UK Parliament Archives 2009-10 |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmhansrd/cmallfiles/mps/commons_hansard_564_os.html |accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Popularity==\nIn 2001, British [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[Robin Cook]] mentioned the dish in a speech acclaiming the benefits of Britain's [[multiculturalism]], declaring:\n{{quote|Chicken tikka masala is now a true British national dish, not only because it is the most popular, but because it is a perfect illustration of the way Britain absorbs and adapts external influences. Chicken tikka is an Indian dish. The masala sauce was added to satisfy the desire of British people to have their meat served in gravy.\"<ref name=Guardian2001>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2001/apr/19/race.britishidentity |title=Robin Cook's chicken tikka masala speech: Extracts from a speech by the foreign secretary to the Social Market Foundation in London |date=19 April 2001 |newspaper=The Guardian }}</ref><ref name=\"Mannur 2009 3\">{{cite book |first=Anita |last=Mannur |title=Culinary Fictions: Food in South Asian Diasporic Culture |year=2009 |publisher=Temple University Press |page=3 |isbn=978-1-4399-0077-2 }}</ref><ref name=\"Collingham 2006 2\">{{cite book |first=E. M. |last=Collingham |title=Curry: A Tale of Cooks and Conquerors |location=Oxford; NY |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2006 |page=[https://archive.org/details/currytaleofcooks00coll/page/2 2] |isbn=0-19-517241-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/currytaleofcooks00coll |url-access=registration }}</ref><ref>Jo Monroe, ''Star of India: The Spicy Adventures of Curry'' (Wiley: 2005 {{ISBN|9780470091883}}) [https://books.google.com/books?id=NC42BaKAwXAC&pg=PA137&dq=chicken+tikka+masala+national+dish&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCQQ6AEwAWoVChMIkJys4fzZxwIVhRU-Ch3HPw4K#v=onepage&q=chicken%20tikka%20masala%20national%20dish&f=false pp. 136-137].</ref>}}\n\nChicken tikka masala is served in restaurants around the world,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kumar|first1=Rakesh|title=Tastes that travel|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/tastes-that-travel/article2241239.ece|website=The Hindu|publisher=Kasturi & Sons Ltd|accessdate=19 May 2017|location=Chennai, India|date=24 February 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Spice of Life |url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1174750,00.html |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |author=Aravind Adiga | date=20 March 2006 |accessdate=1 June 2007}}</ref> including Indian restaurants in Britain and North America. According to a 2012 survey of 2,000 people in Britain, it was the country's second-most popular foreign dish to cook, after [[Stir frying|Chinese stir fry]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/stir-fry-now-britains-most-popular-165120|title=Stir-fry now Britain's most popular foreign dish |work=Daily Mirror| date=21 January 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hills |first1=Suzannah |title=Vindawho? Chicken tikka masala knocked off top spot by Chinese stir-fry as Britain's favourite dish |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2089796/Britains-favourite-dish-Chicken-tikka-masala-knocked-spot-Chinese-stir-fry.html |website=Mail Online |publisher=Associated Newspapers |accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Balti (food)|Balti]], a South Asian dish\n* [[Chicken curry]], a spiced chicken dish\n* [[Butter chicken]], a mild curry dish of Indian origin\n* [[List of chicken dishes]]\n* [[Mughlai cuisine]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Curry Club Tandoori and Tikka Dishes'', Piatkus, London \u2014 {{ISBN|0-7499-1283-9}} (1993)\n*''Curry Club 100 Favourite Tandoori Recipes'', Piatkus, London \u2014 {{ISBN|9780749914912}} (1995)\n* ''India: Food & Cooking'', New Holland, London \u2014 {{ISBN|978-1-84537-619-2}} (2007)\n* {{cite book| last = Collingham| first = Elizabeth M| title = Curry: A Tale of Cooks and Conquerors| publisher = Oxford University Press| year = 2006| pages = [https://archive.org/details/currytaleofcooks00coll/page/2 2]\u20133| isbn = 0-19-517241-8| url = https://archive.org/details/currytaleofcooks00coll| url-access = registration}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Chicken tikka masala}}\n{{cookbook|Chicken Tikka Masala}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Bangladesh|India|Pakistan|United Kingdom|Food}}\n{{English cuisine}}\n{{Bangladeshi dishes}}\n{{Indian Dishes}}\n{{Chicken dishes|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chicken Tikka Masala}}\n[[Category:Indian cuisine in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Indian chicken dishes]]\n[[Category:Indian curries]]\n[[Category:Indian meat dishes]]\n[[Category:Pakistani curries]]\n[[Category:Pakistani chicken dishes]]\n[[Category:Bengali curries]]\n[[Category:Bengali cuisine]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Sylheti cuisine]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cuisine in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Chicken dishes]]\n[[Category:Punjabi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Desi cuisine]]\n[[Category:National dishes]]\n[[Category:Masalas]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Chicken tikka}}\n{{redirect|Chicken masala|the Italian dish|Chicken marsala}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Chicken tikka masala\n| image            = Chicken tikka masala.jpg\n| image_size       = 200px\n| caption          = Chicken tikka masala\n| country          = [[Indian subcontinent]]<br>or [[United Kingdom]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Main course]]\n| served           = Hot\n| main_ingredient  = [[Chicken (food)|Chicken]], [[yogurt]], [[cream]], tomato, onion, garlic, [[ginger]], [[chili pepper]]\n| variations       = Lamb, fish or [[paneer tikka masala]]\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\n[[File:Chicken Tikka Masala KellySue.JPG|thumb|Chicken tikka masala, served atop rice]]\n[[File:Ishwar Chicken Masala.JPG|thumb|Chicken tikka masala in India]]\n'''Chicken tikka masala''' is a dish of chunks of roasted marinated chicken ([[chicken tikka]]) in a spiced [[curry]] sauce. The sauce is usually creamy and orange-coloured. There are multiple claims to its place of origin such as the [[Indian subcontinent]]<ref name=Guardian2001/> and the [[United Kingdom]]. It is among the United Kingdom's most popular dishes.\n\n==Composition==\nChicken tikka masala<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/chicken-tikka-masala|title=Chicken tikka masala {{!}} food|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> is composed of [[chicken tikka]], boneless chunks of chicken marinated in spices and [[yogurt]] that are roasted in an oven, served in a creamy curry sauce.<ref name=\"book\">[[John Lloyd (writer)|Lloyd, J]] and [[John Mitchinson (researcher)|Mitchinson, J]]. ''[[The Book of General Ignorance]]''. Faber & Faber, 2006.</ref> A tomato and [[coriander]] sauce is common, but no recipe for chicken tikka masala is standard; a survey found that of 48 different recipes, the only common ingredient was chicken.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Jackson |first1=Peter |title=A Cultural Politics of Curry in \"Hybrid Cultures, Nervous States: Britain and Germany in a (post)colonial World\"|date=2010|publisher=Rodopi BV|location=Amsterdam|isbn=9789042032286|page=172|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aW4UEN0NUT4C&pg=PA172&lpg=PA172|accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Webb|first1=Andrew|title=Food Britannia|date=2011|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-1847946232|page=177|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FBMLFM305MEC&pg=PA177&lpg=PA177|accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref> The sauce usually includes tomatoes (frequently as [[tomato pur\u00e9e|pur\u00e9e]]), [[cream]], [[coconut cream]] and spices like many versions of its namesake [[masala (spice)|masala]] spice mix. The sauce and chicken pieces may be coloured orange using foodstuffs such as [[turmeric]], [[paprika]], tomato pur\u00e9e or with food dye. The dish shares some similarity with [[butter chicken]], both in the method of creation and appearance.\n\n==Variants==\nVariants of the dish replace chicken with other foodstuffs such as lamb, fish, [[paneer]] or [[Edible mushroom|mushrooms]].\n\n==Origins==\nThe origin of the dish is not certain. Some trace the origins of the dish to the [[British Asian|South Asian community]] in Britain and others claim that the dish was created on the Indian subcontinent. \n\nThe ''Multicultural Handbook of Food, Nutrition and Dietetics'' credits its creation to [[British Bangladeshi|Bangladeshi migrant]] chefs in the 1960s, after migrating from what was then [[East Pakistan]] (now [[Bangladesh]]). At the time, these migrant chefs developed and served a number of new inauthentic \"Indian\" dishes, including chicken tikka masala.<ref name=\"Handbook\">{{cite book |last1=Thaker |first1=Aruna |last2=Barton |first2=Arlene |title=Multicultural Handbook of Food, Nutrition and Dietetics |date=2012 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |isbn=9781405173582 |page=74 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YF1YCg5Ig-EC&pg=PA74}}</ref> Historians of ethnic food Peter and Colleen Grove discuss various origin-claims of chicken tikka masala, concluding that the dish \"was most certainly invented in Britain, probably by a Bangladeshi chef\".<ref name=MenuMag>{{cite web|author1=Grove, Peter |author2=Grove, Colleen|url=http://www.menumagazine.co.uk/book/tikkamasala.html|website=Menu Magazine|publisher=Grove Publications|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127225804/http://www.menumagazine.co.uk/book/tikkamasala.html|archivedate=27 November 2016 |title=Is It or Isn't It? (The Chicken Tikka Masala Story) |date=2008 |accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref> They suggest that \"the shape of things to come may have been a recipe for Shahi Chicken Masala in [[Mrs Balbir Singh]]\u2019s ''Indian Cookery'' published in 1961\".<ref name=MenuMag/>\n\nRahul Verma, a food critic who writes for ''[[The Hindu]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Author profile: Rahul Verma|url=http://www.thehindu.com/profile/author/rahul-verma/|website=The Hindu|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref> said he first tasted the dish in 1971 and that its origins were in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], India. He said \"It's basically a Punjabi dish not more than 40\u201350 years old and must be an accidental discovery which has had periodical improvisations\".<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news |title=Chicken tikka masala debate grows as Indian chefs reprimand Scottish MPs over culinary origins |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/foodanddrink/5972643/Chicken-tikka-masala-row-grows-as-Indian-chefs-reprimand-Scottish-MPs-over-culinary-origins.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | first1=Dean | last1=Nelson | first2=Jalees | last2=Andrabi | date=4 August 2009 | accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Glasgow 2016\"/>\n\nAnother explanation is that it originated in a restaurant in [[Glasgow]], Scotland.<ref name=\"Glasgow 2016\">{{cite news|title=From Charles Mackintosh's waterproof to Dolly the sheep: 43 innovations Scotland has given the world|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/charles-mackintosh-chemist-waterproof-google-doodle-scotland-inventions-innovation-bicycles-a7499911.html|work=The Independent|date=30 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"book\"/> This version recounts how a [[British Pakistani]] chef, Ali Ahmed Aslam, proprietor of the Shish Mahal restaurant in the west end of Glasgow, invented chicken tikka masala by improvising a sauce made from yogurt, cream, and spices.<ref name=\"Glasgow\">{{cite web|title=Glasgow 'invented' Tikka Masala|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/8161812.stm|website=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=21 July 2009|accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Chicken tikka masala claims its origins in Scotland|last1=Godeau| first1=Lucie | agency=Agence France Presse|url=http://www.smh.com.au//breaking-news-world/chicken-tikka-masala-claims-its-origins-in-scotland-20090802-e5mr.html |newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald |date=2 August 2009 |accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref> In 2013, his son Asif Ali told the story of its invention in 1971 to the BBC's ''[[Hairy Bikers]]'' TV cookery programme:<ref name=Bikers/>\n\n{{quote|On a typical dark, wet Glasgow night, a bus driver coming off shift came in and ordered a chicken curry. He sent it back to the waiter saying it's dry. At the time, Dad had an ulcer and was enjoying a plate of tomato soup. So he said why not put some tomato soup into the curry with some spices. They sent it back to the table and the bus driver absolutely loved it. He and his friends came back again and again and we put it on the menu.<ref name=Bikers>BBC Hairy Bikers' Best of British Series 2: 5. Food and the Empire. First shown: 6.30pm 5 April 2013</ref>}}\n\nIn July 2009, then British Member of Parliament [[Mohammad Sarwar (politician)|Mohammad Sarwar]] [[Table (parliamentary procedure)|tabled]] an [[Early Day Motion]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] asking that Parliament support a campaign for Glasgow to be given [[Geographical indications and traditional specialities in the European Union|European Union protected geographical status]] for chicken tikka masala.<ref>{{cite web |title=UK Parliament Early Day Motions 2008-2009 |url=http://edmi.parliament.uk/EDMi/EDMDetails.aspx?EDMID=39136&SESSION=899 |accessdate=11 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222052029/http://edmi.parliament.uk/EDMi/EDMDetails.aspx?EDMID=39136&SESSION=899 |archive-date=22 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Early Day Motion #1911 |url=https://edm.parliament.uk/early-day-motion/39136/glasgow-chicken-tikka-masala |website=House of Commons |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> The motion was not chosen for debate, nor did Sarwar speak on this subject in Parliament.<ref>{{cite web |title=UK Parliament Archives 2008-9 |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200809/cmhansrd/cmallfiles/mps/commons_hansard_564_os.html |accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=UK Parliament Archives 2009-10 |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmhansrd/cmallfiles/mps/commons_hansard_564_os.html |accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Popularity==\nIn 2001, British [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[Robin Cook]] mentioned the dish in a speech acclaiming the benefits of Britain's [[multiculturalism]], declaring:\n{{quote|Chicken tikka masala is now a true British national dish, not only because it is the most popular, but because it is a perfect illustration of the way Britain absorbs and adapts external influences. Chicken tikka is an Indian dish. The masala sauce was added to satisfy the desire of British people to have their meat served in gravy.\"<ref name=Guardian2001>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2001/apr/19/race.britishidentity |title=Robin Cook's chicken tikka masala speech: Extracts from a speech by the foreign secretary to the Social Market Foundation in London |date=19 April 2001 |newspaper=The Guardian }}</ref><ref name=\"Mannur 2009 3\">{{cite book |first=Anita |last=Mannur |title=Culinary Fictions: Food in South Asian Diasporic Culture |year=2009 |publisher=Temple University Press |page=3 |isbn=978-1-4399-0077-2 }}</ref><ref name=\"Collingham 2006 2\">{{cite book |first=E. M. |last=Collingham |title=Curry: A Tale of Cooks and Conquerors |location=Oxford; NY |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2006 |page=[https://archive.org/details/currytaleofcooks00coll/page/2 2] |isbn=0-19-517241-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/currytaleofcooks00coll |url-access=registration }}</ref><ref>Jo Monroe, ''Star of India: The Spicy Adventures of Curry'' (Wiley: 2005 {{ISBN|9780470091883}}) [https://books.google.com/books?id=NC42BaKAwXAC&pg=PA137&dq=chicken+tikka+masala+national+dish&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCQQ6AEwAWoVChMIkJys4fzZxwIVhRU-Ch3HPw4K#v=onepage&q=chicken%20tikka%20masala%20national%20dish&f=false pp. 136-137].</ref>}}\n\nChicken tikka masala is served in restaurants around the world,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kumar|first1=Rakesh|title=Tastes that travel|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/tastes-that-travel/article2241239.ece|website=The Hindu|publisher=Kasturi & Sons Ltd|accessdate=19 May 2017|location=Chennai, India|date=24 February 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Spice of Life |url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1174750,00.html |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |author=Aravind Adiga | date=20 March 2006 |accessdate=1 June 2007}}</ref> including Indian restaurants in Britain and North America. According to a 2012 survey of 2,000 people in Britain, it was the country's second-most popular foreign dish to cook, after [[Stir frying|Chinese stir fry]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/stir-fry-now-britains-most-popular-165120|title=Stir-fry now Britain's most popular foreign dish |work=Daily Mirror| date=21 January 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hills |first1=Suzannah |title=Vindawho? Chicken tikka masala knocked off top spot by Chinese stir-fry as Britain's favourite dish |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2089796/Britains-favourite-dish-Chicken-tikka-masala-knocked-spot-Chinese-stir-fry.html |website=Mail Online |publisher=Associated Newspapers |accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Balti (food)|Balti]], a South Asian dish\n* [[Chicken curry]], a spiced chicken dish\n* [[Butter chicken]], a mild curry dish of Indian origin\n* [[List of chicken dishes]]\n* [[Mughlai cuisine]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Curry Club Tandoori and Tikka Dishes'', Piatkus, London \u2014 {{ISBN|0-7499-1283-9}} (1993)\n*''Curry Club 100 Favourite Tandoori Recipes'', Piatkus, London \u2014 {{ISBN|9780749914912}} (1995)\n* ''India: Food & Cooking'', New Holland, London \u2014 {{ISBN|978-1-84537-619-2}} (2007)\n* {{cite book| last = Collingham| first = Elizabeth M| title = Curry: A Tale of Cooks and Conquerors| publisher = Oxford University Press| year = 2006| pages = [https://archive.org/details/currytaleofcooks00coll/page/2 2]\u20133| isbn = 0-19-517241-8| url = https://archive.org/details/currytaleofcooks00coll| url-access = registration}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Chicken tikka masala}}\n{{cookbook|Chicken Tikka Masala}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Bangladesh|India|Pakistan|United Kingdom|Food}}\n{{English cuisine}}\n{{Bangladeshi dishes}}\n{{Indian Dishes}}\n{{Chicken dishes|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chicken Tikka Masala}}\n[[Category:Indian cuisine in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Indian chicken dishes]]\n[[Category:Indian curries]]\n[[Category:Indian meat dishes]]\n[[Category:Pakistani curries]]\n[[Category:Pakistani chicken dishes]]\n[[Category:Bengali curries]]\n[[Category:Bengali cuisine]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Sylheti cuisine]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cuisine in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Chicken dishes]]\n[[Category:Punjabi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Desi cuisine]]\n[[Category:National dishes]]\n[[Category:Masalas]]\n", "name_user": "117.230.27.2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicken_tikka_masala"}
{"title_page": "Krystina Alabado", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress and singer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Krystina Alabado\n| image         =\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date  =  {{birth date and age|1989|08|07}}{{fact|date=May 2019}}\n| birth_place   =\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   =\n| othername   = \n| education = [[Arizona State University]]<br>{{small|(did not graduate)}}\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n*Actress\n*singer}}\n| years_active  = 2009\u2013present\n| spouse = {{marriage|Robert Lenzi|2017}}\n| children = \n}}\n\n'''Krystina Alabado''' is an American actress and singer known for her work in [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musicals. She originated the supporting role of Vanden in the 2016 Broadway production of ''[[American Psycho (musical)|American Psycho]]'', and currently stars as Gretchen Wieners in ''[[Mean Girls (musical)|Mean Girls]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nAlabado attended [[Hamilton High School (Chandler, Arizona)|Hamilton High School]] in [[Chandler, Arizona]] and studied musical theatre for one year at [[Arizona State University]].<ref name=\"azc-2016\">{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/arts/2016/05/05/krystina-alabado-american-psycho-broadway/83943660/|title=Arizona actress stars in \u2018American Psycho\u2019 on Broadway|website=azcentral|accessdate=19 May 2019|date=5 May 2016}}</ref> Alabado's parents are immigrants from [[Mexico]] and [[Lebanon]].<ref name=\"azc-2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/arts/2019/03/17/arizona-actor-krystina-alabado-back-broadway-mean-girls/3148685002/|title=That\u2019s so fetch! Arizona actor Krystina Alabado is back on Broadway in \u2018Mean Girls\u2019|website=azcentral|accessdate=19 May 2019|date=17 March 2019}}</ref> She identifies as [[Latinas|Latina]].<ref name=\"insta-2016\">{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BKUSxw1Dx0C/|title=Krystina Alabado on Instagram: \"Day One \u2714\ufe0f I have never been more proud to be a daughter, a Latina, a woman, and a human being. This new piece I am working on at La Jolla\u2026\"|website=Instagram|accessdate=19 May 2019|date=13 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAt the age of 18, Alabado joined the national tour of ''[[Spring Awakening (musical)|Spring Awakening]]'' as part of the ensemble. In 2009, she moved to New York City,<ref name=\"amny-2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amny.com/entertainment/mean-girls-broadway-1.29330328|title='Mean Girls' has a fetch new Gretchen Wieners|website=am New York|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> and made her Broadway debut in 2011 as an ensemble replacement<ref name=\"playbill\">{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/person/krystina-alabado-vault-0000117621|title=Krystina Alabado|website=Playbill|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> in ''[[American Idiot (musical)|American Idiot]]'', later also participating in a touring production.<ref name=\"azc-2016\"/> In 2013, she joined a national tour of ''[[Evita (musical)|Evita]]'' (based on the [[Evita (musical)#2012 Broadway revival|2012 Broadway revival]]) playing Juan Per\u00f3n's mistress.<ref name=\"evita-tour\">{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Josh-Young-and-Caroline-Bowman-Set-to-Lead-EVITA-National-Tour-and-Che-and-Eva--Full-Cast-Announced-20130716|title=Josh Young, Caroline Bowman and Sean MacLaughlin Set to Lead EVITA National Tour- Full Cast Announced!|first=BWW News|last=Desk|website=BroadwayWorld.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> In 2016, she appeared in the short-lived Broadway production of ''[[American Psycho (musical)|American Psycho]]''. Alabado performed in the ensemble and as the minor character Vanden, a nightclub singer.<ref name=\"azc-2016\"/> She also [[understudied]] the principal role of Jean.<ref name=\"playbill\"/>\n\nIn March 2019, Alabado joined the cast of ''[[Mean Girls (musical)|Mean Girls]]'' as Gretchen Wieners, replacing [[Ashley Park (actress)|Ashley Park]], who originated the role.<ref name=\"playbill-mg-replacement\">{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/krystina-alabado-joins-broadway-cast-of-mean-girls-march-12|title=Krystina Alabado Joins Broadway Cast of Mean Girls March 12|first=Ryan|last=McPhee|date=12 March 2019|website=Playbill|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Alabado began a YouTube account to explain to her followers different aspects of how Broadway works and interview her fellow castmates during the COVID-19 pandemic that temporarily closed Broadway.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCjj8fPyRRk8HpqI2HWKZE0w|title=Krystina Alabado|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Theatre credits ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%\" \n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Theatre\n! Director(s)\n! {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Spring Awakening (musical)|Spring Awakening]]''\n| Ensemble {{small|(u/s Wendla/Ilse)}}\n| U.S. National Tour\n| {{small|[[Michael Mayer (director)|Michael Mayer]]}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet the Cast |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226031630/http://www.springawakening.com/tourcast_detail.php?id=39 |website=Spring Awakening |date=December 26, 2009}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2011\n| ''Camp Wanatachi''\n| Titi O\u2019Malley\n| [[La MaMa Experimental Theatre Club]]\n| {{small|Matt Cowart}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/off-broadway/article/Cast-And-Producers-Announced-For-CAMP-WANATACHI-At-La-MaMa-ETC-12126-20110105 |title=Cast And Producers Announced For CAMP WANATACHI At La MaMa E.T.C. 1/21-2/6 |first= |last= |date=January 5, 2011 |website=Broadway World}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''' ''[[American Idiot (musical)|American Idiot]]'' '''\n| '''Ensemble''' {{small|(replacement)}}\n| '''[[St. James Theatre]]'''\n| rowspan=2 | {{small|Michael Mayer}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/american-idiot-will-close-april-24-billie-joe-armstrong-will-